05721nam a22008055i 9781447342519DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20072007xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a9781447342519  a(DE-B1597)646709  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-BST 7aPOL0280002bisacsh00aMaking policy in theory and practice /ced. by Hugh Bochel, Sue Duncan. 1aBristol : bPolicy Press, c[2007] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of tables and figures -- tList of abbreviations -- tNotes on contributors -- tIntroduction -- tForward-looking policy making -- tOutward-looking policy making -- tInnovative, flexible and creative policy making -- tEvidence-based policy making -- tInclusive policy making -- tJoined-up policy making -- tPolicy review -- tPolicy evaluation -- tLearning lessons from policy experience -- tConclusions -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis unique book combines both academic and practitioner perspectives to provide critical consideration of contemporary policy-making and highlight examples of good practice at all levels of government. In Professional Policy Making for the Twenty-First Century the Cabinet Office's Strategic Policy Making Team identified nine 'competencies' as the key features of 'modern policy making': forward-looking; outward-looking; innovative, flexible and creative; evidence-based; inclusive; joined-up; open to review; open to evaluation; and capable of learning lessons. Using these to structure the book, nine central chapters - each written by a pair of co-authors, one primarily an academic, and the other primarily a policy maker or practitioner - examine the competencies in turn. Accompanying case studies provide lessons or pointers to good practice, together with guidance on how to access further information. Set in the context of New Labour's emphasis on 'modernisation', and reflecting the growing emphasis on policy making as a skill, the book will appeal to a range of audiences, including undergraduate and postgraduate students on courses that draw upon approaches to public administration and public policy, and social researchers, policy officers and others involved in the development and analysis of policy making at all tiers of government.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh1 aBochel, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBochel, Hugh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBochel, Hugh, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBulmer, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoates, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDominian, Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuncan, Sue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuncan, Sue, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEvans, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHudson, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKerr, Marion, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMark-Lawson, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMassey, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaynard, Warwick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPage, Edward C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParry, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https